1 Problem 1.

We will be using a dataset from a study on the impacts of image acquisition method on measures of brain activity. FMRI is a non-invasive technique that can be used to measure brain activity across time. Resting-state fMRI is acquired while a participant stares at a crosshair and performs no specific task. Nine 6-min rs-fMRI scans were collected on 32 healthy young adults. Scans differed by their “multiband factor,” which is a technique that allows more time points to be collected in the same amount of time. Although more data is collected, the data may be noisier. The data measures activity between two brain regions: one is located in the left thalamus and the other in the right thalamus. The thalamus relays information between brain regions.

We will examine whether brain activity differs when measured using two acquisitions: SB.3.3 and MB.4. SB.3.3.mm is a single-band acquisition with larger voxels, and similar acquisitions were used in most studies prior to around 2016. MB4 is an accelerated sequence that collects more data in the same amount of time, and in this study, used a 2 mm acquisition. We collected these data in my lab, and the paper is available here.

We will focus on the following variables:

id is subject ID.

zcor is the measure of brain activity (a Fisher z-fransformed correlation)

Acquisition is the scan used to acquire the data.

The data are in the “long” format.

1.1

First, use the lm() function to compare the mean brain activity in SB.3.3.mm to MB.4, and print the output of summary(). No need to interpret the results yet. You can use the code below to subset to these two acquisitions. Note the use of %in%, which is a helpful R function.

# set the working directory
# read in the dataset
mbdata = read.csv("thalamus_mb_selected.csv")
# subset the dataset
mbdata_sel = mbdata[mbdata$Acquisition %in% c("SB.3.3.mm","MB.4"),c("id","Acquisition","zcor")]
# fit the linear model
model.lm = lm(zcor~Acquisition,data=mbdata_sel)
# output the summary() results
summary(model.lm)

1.2

Now check model diagnostics using plot(). Describe each of the four plots and any issues.

# arrange the plots
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
# plot the diagnostics plots
plot(model.lm)
## hat values (leverages) are all = 0.03225806
##  and there are no factor predictors; no plot no. 5

The first plot is used to check the linearity assumption. Since there is only a single binary variable, this line is flat.

The second plot is used to check the normality assumption. There are some departures in the tails.

The third plot is used to check the homoscedasticity. As can be seen, the red line slightly increases, indicating that the variance is somewhat higher in one of the acquisitions than in the other (here, SB.3.3.mm is slightly higher than MB.4).

The last plot is used to check the outliers. Data points 25, 258 and 77 have larger standardized residuals. The plot is titled ‘Constant Leverage’ because all points have the same leverage value of 0.03226 (which can be verified using hatvalues(model.lm)). This is because there is only a single binary variable.

1.3

Based on what we know about the data, are there any other model assumptions that may be violated?

The assumption of independence may be violated. SB.3.3.mm and MB.4 are repeatedly measured on the same subject, which are not independent.

Next we will use a t-test to compare SB.3.3.mm and MB.4. It is helpful to reshape the data into “wide” format.

library(tidyr)
mbdata_sel_wide = mbdata_sel %>% pivot_wider(names_from = Acquisition, values_from = zcor)

Conduct a t-test using t.test(). For this problem, use paired=FALSE and var.equal=TRUE. How do the estimates, t-statistic, and p-value compare to lm()?

t.test(mbdata_sel_wide$SB.3.3.mm,mbdata_sel_wide$MB.4, paired = FALSE, var.equal=TRUE)

The two sample t-test is used to test the null hypothesis that there is no difference between two group means. Based on the results above, we reject the null hypothesis (\(p<0.05\)) and conclude that the difference between the mean zcor measured in SB.3.3.mm and MB.4 is statistically significant. The results will be exactly the same as one from lm().

How do the estimates, t-statistics, degrees of freedom, and p values compare in the paired and unpaired versions? (Compare the paired t.test to the t.test with paired=FALSE and var.equal=FALSE from the previous problem.)

The paired t-test has a larger estimates (0.328 vs. 0.886 - 0.575 = 0.311), larger t-statistic (5.1113 vs. 4.4136), smaller degrees of freedom (29 vs. 56.189), and smaller p-value (1.862e-05 vs. 4.664e-05) compared to the previous unpaired t-test with var.equal=FALSE.

Here, the estimate of the difference in mean differs from the previous questions because a couple participants were missing one of the acquisitions. When all the data are the same, the estimate of the difference does not vary between the paired and unpaired t-tests. See the example below:

temp = mbdata_sel_wide[complete.cases(mbdata_sel_wide),]

1.10

Now calculate the standard error of the paired t-test using the variance of MB.4, SB.3.3.mm, and their covariance. Do this using the R functions var() as well as cov(). Check that your value matches the SE output by the paired t-test, which can be viewed using t.test()$stderr. (Use the discussion board if you have issues or questions.) Does the covariance increase or decrease the test statistic? Hint: subset to complete observations before doing this, e.g., mydata[complete.cases(mydata),]

# subset complete observations
mbtemp = mbdata_sel_wide[complete.cases(mbdata_sel_wide),]
sqrt((var(mbtemp$MB.4)+var(mbtemp$SB.3.3.mm)-2*cov(mbtemp$MB.4,mbtemp$SB.3.3.mm))/nrow(mbtemp))
## [1] 0.06422296
# SE output by the paired t-test
t.test(diff)$stderr
## [1] 0.06422296

The covariance increases the test statistic.

Additional information: In general, the covariance helps statistical power in a paired t-test because it is usually positive, and hence when subtracted, leads to a smaller standard error, which leads to a larger test statistic. For example, in experimental design, an experiment examining the effect of a drug is generally more powerful when an outcome is observed before and after a drug than say an experimental design that examines one cohort on a drug and a second cohort off the drug.

1.11

How does brain activity in the thalamus measured using the multiband 4 with 2 mm resolution compare to single band with 3.3 mm resolution? State your null hypothesis, report the p value and state your conclusion, along with your chosen \(\alpha\)-level.

A paired t-test is used to test the null hypothesis that there is no difference between mean brain activity in the thalamus measured using the multiband 4 with 2 mm resolution compare to single band with 3.3 mm resolution. The p-value for paired t-test is 1.862e-05. Given an \(\alpha\) level of 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the difference between the mean brain activity in the thalamus measured in SB.3.3.mm and MB.4 is statistically significant.

2 Problem 2.

Dataset: parkinsons.csv

In this problem, we will examine whether dysphonia, or abnormal speech sounds, are related to Parkinson’s disease severity. This dataset was obtained from https://data.world/uci/parkinsons-telemonitoring/. The response variable we will examine is motor_UPDRS (motor Unified Parkinson’s Disease Rating Scale). The scientific question is whether Parkinson’s severity can be monitored using features derived from speech recordings, which can be collected by telephone. The gold standard for monitoring disease progression, the UPDRS, is administered in a clinic, and hence is costly and burdensome.

There are nearly 6000 observations in this dataset, which are collected on 42 subjects.

2.2

Why were coefficients for age and sex not estimated? Mathematically, what can we say about the columns of the design matrix?

This is because the design matrix is a sigular matrix rather than full rank , that is, the columns of the design matrix are not linearly independent with each other. Mathematically, the columns corresponding to sex and age are linear combinations of the columns corresponding to the other independent variables.

2.5

Without looking at the diagnostic plots, which of the assumptions of linear regression is (or are) violated?

The assumption of independence may be violated. The measurements at different test times are collected on 42 subjects. Hence, the measurements of the same subject are not independent.

2.6

Perform model diagnostics using plot(). Summarize your interpretation of each of the four plots and whether there are any concerns.

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(model2.3)

The first plot is used to check the linearity assumption and homoscedasticity. The red line is not flat, which indicates a violation of the linearity assumption.

The second plot is used to check the normality assumption. It shows some departures at the tails, suggesting a potential violation of normality.

The third plot is used to check the homoscedasticity. By looking at the red line, it is almost flat with minor fluctuations, which doesn’t indicate a severe violation of the homoscedasticity assumption. However, there are two clusters of points in the plot, with the cluster on the left with smaller variance, indicating a possible violation of homoscedasticity.

The last plot is used to check the outliers and influential points. We identified three potential outliers with both large leverages and standardized residuals (4064, 1881, 4107) in the plot. However, they are not flagged as being influential points using Cook’s distance (Cook’s distance < 1), so it is less likely that they are highly influential.

2.7

Fit the model without age. Does the coefficient of NHR change? Calculate \((\beta_{no-age} - \beta_{adjusted})/\beta_{no-age}\). Here, \(\beta_{no-age}\) is the slope of NHR in the model without age and \(\beta_{adjusted}\) is the slope of NHR in the model from 2.4. Is there evidence of omitted variable bias?

model2.4 = lm(motor_UPDRS~sex+Jitter_Percent+Shimmer+NHR+PPE,data=pdata)

beta_no_age <- coef(model2.4)["NHR"] 
beta_adjusted <- coef(model2.3)["NHR"] 
percent_change <- ((beta_no_age - beta_adjusted) / beta_no_age) * 100
percent_change
##       NHR 
## -260.1274

The coefficient of NHR decreases by around 260% after excluding age, indicating omitted variable bias.

2.9

Interpret the slope of NHR in the model including age*NHR. Is this biologically reasonable?

After controlling for the other covariates in the model, one unit increase in NHR is associated with 134.66364 increases in motor_UPDRS for people at age = 0. This interpretation is not biologically reasonable since there is no valid situation where someone can have an age of 0.
